      <p>That grinding, squealing noise coming from your LG dryer isn't something you can ignore. I've been fixing these machines for fifteen years, and nine times out of ten when someone calls about dryer noise, it's the drum bearings starting to fail.</p>
<h2>Common Causes of LG Dryer Noise During Operation</h2>
<p>The first thing we check when your LG dryer sounds like a freight train is the drum bearing assembly. These bearings support the entire weight of your drum and clothes load, spinning thousands of times per load. When they start wearing out, you'll hear that telltale grinding or squealing, especially when the drum is loaded with wet clothes. Most homeowners don't realize that continuing to run a dryer with bad bearings can damage the drum itself, turning a $150 bearing replacement into a $400 drum and bearing job. The noise usually starts subtle - maybe just during heavy loads - then gets progressively worse until it sounds like metal grinding on metal.</p>
<h3>Early Warning Signs of Bearing Failure</h3>
<p>Before the grinding gets unbearable, your LG dryer will give you warning signs. You might notice the drum wobbling slightly when you open the door, or hear intermittent squeaking during the spin cycle. Some models make a rumbling sound that gets louder as the load gets heavier. Don't wait until it sounds like a construction site - early replacement saves money and prevents secondary damage.</p>
<h2>Drum Bearing Problems: Signs and Solutions</h2>
<p>When drum bearings fail in LG dryers, the symptoms are pretty consistent across all models, whether you've got a DLEX or DLGX series. The bearing assembly sits at the back of the drum, and when it starts going bad, you'll feel excessive play when you manually spin the drum with the door open. We see this problem most often in units that are 4-7 years old, especially if they've been overloaded regularly. The repair involves pulling the drum completely out, which means disconnecting the belt, removing the front panel, and carefully extracting the drum assembly. It's not a simple weekend DIY project - the drum alone weighs about 30 pounds, and you need specific tools to press the old bearing out and the new one in.</p>
<h3>OEM vs Aftermarket Bearing Quality</h3>
<p>We only use OEM LG bearings because the aftermarket ones fail within 18 months. I've seen too many callbacks from customers who tried to save $30 on a cheaper bearing only to have the same noise return a year later. LG bearings are engineered for the specific weight and balance of their drums, and that precision matters when you're talking about thousands of rotations per day.</p>
<h2>Belt and Pulley System Troubleshooting</h2>
<p>Sometimes what sounds like bearing noise is actually a worn belt or misaligned pulley system. The drive belt wraps around the drum and connects to the motor pulley, and when it starts stretching or fraying, it can create squealing or thumping sounds that mimic bearing problems. A quick way to check this yourself is to open the dryer door and look for black rubber dust around the drum - that's a sure sign the belt is deteriorating. However, don't assume it's just the belt if you're hearing metal-on-metal grinding. Belt replacement is straightforward, but proper tension adjustment requires experience. Too loose and it slips, too tight and it puts excessive strain on the motor and bearings.</p>
<h3>When Pulleys Need Attention</h3>
<p>The motor pulley and idler pulley can develop worn grooves or bent edges that cause belt tracking problems. We inspect these components during every belt replacement because a new belt on a worn pulley will fail prematurely. Most homeowners focus only on the belt, but the pulleys are equally important for smooth, quiet operation.</p>
<h2>Lint Buildup: Hidden Noise Culprit</h2>
<p>You'd be surprised how often excessive lint buildup causes noise problems that get blamed on bearings. Lint accumulates not just in the filter, but throughout the entire air path, including around the blower wheel and inside the cabinet. When lint wraps around the blower wheel, it creates an imbalance that causes vibration and noise. Plus, restricted airflow makes the motor work harder, which can accelerate bearing wear. We've found tennis balls, socks, and massive lint clogs wedged behind drums in homes throughout Pasadena and Burbank. The noise stops immediately once we clean everything out, and the dryer runs quieter than it has in years.</p>
<h3>Professional Deep Cleaning Benefits</h3>
<p>A thorough dryer cleaning involves disassembling the unit to access areas you can't reach with a vacuum hose. We remove lint from the blower housing, clean the moisture sensors, and check the exhaust duct connection. This service often eliminates mystery noises and improves drying efficiency by 30-40%. It's preventive maintenance that extends the life of expensive components like motors and bearings.</p>
<h2>When Worn Drum Rollers Need Replacement</h2>
<p>LG dryers use drum support rollers on the front and sometimes rear of the drum assembly. These plastic or nylon rollers can wear flat spots or develop cracks, causing rhythmic thumping noises that coincide with drum rotation. Unlike bearings, roller noise is usually more of a thumping than grinding, and it's often worse with lighter loads when there's less weight to dampen the vibration. Roller replacement is less involved than bearing work, but still requires partial disassembly. The key is replacing all the rollers at once, even if only one seems worn. They wear at similar rates, so replacing just one means you'll be back in there within six months for the others.</p>
<h3>Identifying Roller vs Bearing Issues</h3>
<p>Here's how to tell the difference: bearing noise is consistent grinding that doesn't change rhythm, while roller noise thumps in time with drum rotation. You can sometimes feel the flat spots if you manually rotate the drum slowly. Bearing problems get worse under load, roller problems are often more noticeable with small loads that don't weigh down the drum.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>Why does my LG dryer make grinding noise when spinning?</h3>
<p>That grinding noise is almost always worn drum bearings. The bearing assembly supports the entire drum weight, and after years of use, the bearing surfaces wear down and start making metal-on-metal contact. It starts subtle but gets progressively worse. Don't ignore it - continuing to run the dryer with bad bearings can damage the drum itself.</p>
<h3>How much does it cost to replace LG dryer drum bearings?</h3>
<p>Drum bearing replacement typically runs $180-220 including labor and OEM parts. That includes our $65 diagnostic fee. The job takes about 90 minutes because we have to remove the drum completely. Some customers ask about aftermarket bearings to save money, but I don't recommend them - they fail within 18 months and you'll be paying for the same repair twice.</p>
<h3>Can I fix a noisy LG dryer belt myself?</h3>
<p>Belt replacement is doable if you're handy, but proper tension adjustment is tricky. Too loose and it slips, too tight and you'll damage the motor. The bigger issue is that belt problems often indicate worn pulleys or other components that need professional inspection. We see a lot of DIY belt jobs that work for a few months then fail because the underlying cause wasn't addressed.</p>
<h3>When should I replace my LG dryer instead of repairing it?</h3>
<p>If your dryer is over 10 years old and needs bearing replacement plus other major components like a motor or control board, replacement makes more sense financially. But for bearing-only problems on units under 8 years old, repair is definitely the way to go. A good bearing job should give you another 5-7 years of service.</p>
<h3>How often should I clean my LG dryer to prevent noise?</h3>
<p>Clean the lint filter after every load, obviously, but have the internal components professionally cleaned every 2-3 years. Lint buildup around the blower wheel causes vibration and noise that people often mistake for bearing problems. We've eliminated mysterious noises in dozens of dryers just with a thorough cleaning.</p>
